Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: No use or possession of a controlled substance or drug-related paraphernalia without a valid prescription.

1:49 PM Prosecuting attorney Peter James Marvin Kruger in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Malia Lee Jamison appeared by video, in custody. Attorney Michael Hoffman appears via video on behalf of Defendant Malia Jamison. Attorney Hoffman verified address. Attorney Hoffman received information, waives reading and requests preliminary hearing. State requests $3,000 cash bail and condition of no use or possession of a controlled substance or drug-related paraphernalia without a valid prescription. Defendant has five priors with a fta on $100 cash bail. Attorney Hoffman notes defendant is a local resident and has two children that live locally. Defendant is not employed at the moment. Defendant unsure about amount that she can post about $500 at maximum and disagrees she had a failure to appear. Court questions defendant on amount she can post. Court orders $1,000 cash bail with condition of no use or possession of a controlled substance or drug-related paraphernalia without a valid prescription.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for July 27, 2022 at 10:15 am.
